[{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<p class=\"direction_paragraph\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">This question is a long free-response question. Show your work for each part of the question. (15 points, suggested time 25 minutes)</p>\n\n<div>\n<div class=\"stimulus_reference\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents two conducting spheres, labeled Sphere A and Sphere B, each with a radius of R. Sphere A has a charge of negative 5 microcoulombs, and Sphere B has a charge of negative 20 microcoulombs.\" height=\"120\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252443.g01.png\" width=\"275\" /></div>\n\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<p class=\"passage_para\">The figure above shows two conducting spheres that are very far apart. The spheres have the same radius <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"R\"><math alttext=\"R\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and the different negative charges shown. Outside the spheres, the charge on each sphere can be treated as if it were at the center of the sphere.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"item_part part_id:A part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"A\">\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(a) Compare the magnitude of the electric field at the surface of sphere A to the magnitude of the electric field at the surface of sphere B. Justify your answer.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:B part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"B\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Consider two scenarios, one in which an individual electron is moved from far away to a position outside one of the spheres at a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the surface, and the other in which an individual proton is moved in the same manner.</p><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(b) An external force must do non-zero work to move each particle to the distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Indicate whether the sign of the work is the same for both the electron and the proton. Justify your answer using the concepts of electric fields or forces.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:C part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"C\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(c) Compare the magnitude of the work required to move an electron to a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the surface of sphere A to the magnitude of the work required to move an electron to a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the surface of sphere B. Justify your answer using the concepts of electric fields or forces.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:D part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"D\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(d) When an electron with charge of magnitude e is brought from far away to a distance d from the center of one of the spheres, the electron-sphere system experiences a change in potential energy of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U\"><math alttext=\"delta U\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>U</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The equation for this change is <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta U equals, the fraction with numerator k times e, times Q, and denominator d\"><math alttext=\"delta U equals, the fraction with numerator k times e, times Q, and denominator d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>U</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>k</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>Q</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>, where <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"k equals, the fraction with numerator 1, and denominator 4 pi times epsilon sub 0, end fraction\"><math alttext=\"k equals, the fraction with numerator 1, and denominator 4 pi times epsilon sub 0, end fraction\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>k</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>π</mi><msub><mrow><mi>ε</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Use this equation to compare the magnitude of the change in potential energy of the electron-sphere A system to that of the electron-sphere B system when the electron is brought from far away to a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from the center of each sphere. Explain your reasoning.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:E part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"E\"><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(e) Is your answer from part (d) consistent with your answer from part (c)? Justify your answer using physics principles.</p></div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:F part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"F\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure shows two point charges, labeled F and G, and a point labeled P. Point charge F has a charge of positive 3 microcoulombs, and it is located at a distance of L vertically above point P. Point charge G has a charge of negative 18 microcoulombs, and it is located at a distance of L horizontally to the right of Point P. To the right are coordinate axes with positive x to the right and positive y toward the top of the page.\" height=\"214\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252443.g02.png\" width=\"360\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">Two point charges, F and G, have the charges shown in the figure above. Each charge is a distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"L\"><math alttext=\"L\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>L</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. The electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> due to charge F has magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub F\"><math alttext=\"E sub F\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>F</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>.</p>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(f) Describe the magnitude and direction of the net electric field at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"P\"><math alttext=\"P\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> due to both charges in terms of <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"E sub F\"><math alttext=\"E sub F\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><msub><mrow><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>F</mtext></mrow></msub></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and with respect to the coordinate axes shown. If the net electric field is not directed along an axis, indicate to which axis the direction of the net electric field is closest. If the direction of the net electric field is exactly in the middle (<span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"45 degrees\"><math alttext=\"45 degrees\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mn>45</mn><mi>°</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> from each axis), state this explicitly. Explain your reasoning using relevant physics principles.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"},{"id":"VR252443","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"<div class=\"item_part part_id:G part_name:ExtendedText response_class:FreeResponse response_type:Essay\" id=\"G\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents four figures labeled Figure 1 through Figure 4. Each figure is a diagram that shows dots for the locations of point charges F and G near the upper left and lower right, respectively, and isolines of electric potential. The locations of point charges F and G match the locations of the point charges in the previous diagram where point charge F has a charge of positive 3 microcoulombs and point charge G has a charge of negative 18 microcoulombs. All four figures contain some circular isolines around each dot and some other isolines. Figure 1 has larger circles around the lower right dot than around the upper left dot, and parts of some other isolines that surround only one of the dots. Figure 2 has larger circles around the lower right dot than around the upper left dot, and then parts of some isolines that surround both dots. Figure 3 has sets of circular isolines of the same size around each dot, and parts of some isolines that surround both dots. Figure 4 has sets of circular isolines of the same size around each dot, and a straight isoline midway between the dots.\" height=\"354\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VR252443.g03.png\" width=\"355\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"stem_paragraph\">(g) The diagrams shown above depict isolines of electric potential. Which diagram best depicts the isolines of electric potential of charges F and G? Explain your reasoning.</p>\n</div>\n","rubricRef":"VR252443_rubric"}]